column1: From March through August 2017, how many months will see Macau's monthly gross gaming revenues exceeding 2016 monthly revenues by 10% or more?
column6: ['Business']
column11: March through August gross revenues exceeded 2016 revenues by 10% or more. This question closed with an answer of "d) all 6 months", with and end date of 1 September 2017. (Macau Gaming Inspection and Co-ordination Bureau) Gaming revenues fell precipitously in 2014 and 2015 as President Xi Jinping's anti-graft campaign deterred Chinese high-rollers from flaunting their wealth in Macau's casinos, but have started to climb again (The Economist, Bloomberg, Business Times). The question will be resolved according to official data provided by the Macau Gaming Inspection and Co-ordination Bureau here. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

Well I have made a truly absurd number of predictions for a silly questions but here is one more. I now think it'll be all six months because revenues have been way up all year.
Updating from 0/0/10/90 thanks to info from @Dsarin [1].
Revenue over the last six months (February to July) increased between 16.3% and 29.2% over the corresponding month of 2016. However, January 2017 was only 3.1% more than Jan 2016.

The question asks from Mar through August, 5 months have seen greater revenues than last year. It is very probable that the last month will be the same. Monthly revenue has varied in the band from +13.0% to +18.
Macau fears have died down, VIP's are back gambling again, and gaming revenues have risen each month for the last 11 months. Barring a disaster, it should be all 6 months.
They appear to be on a roll, should continue and will likely be much higher than 10%

the last 5 months have been over 10%. The first 3 were between 10-20%, the last 2 have been over 20%, no reason to think this trend is going to change.

Looking at the data, Macau has already had 3 months (March, April, May) with monthly gross gambling revenues exceeding 2016 revenues by more than 10%. It seems highly likely that there will be at least 1 more, probably 2 more months where this occurs.

Revenues in the world's biggest casino hub of Macau jumped 24 percent in May, beating expectations and posting a 10-month winning streak as wealthy gamblers returned to the southern Chinese territory despite a corruption crackdown.
Macau is posting consistently higher returns and I'm shifting hard toward all six month as I think this trend continues.
